 A technology firm and an e-commerce platform, QShop, is empowering Nigerian Small and Medium Scale Enterprises (SMEs) through access to local and international markets. In two years, SMEs have processed about N300 million ($500,000) worth of transactions on the platform. QShop provides access to the tools, resources and community that SMEs need to thrive online, enabling them to meet personal business targets, improve global competitiveness and reach their full potential as major contributors to economic growth. Briefing newsmen on how the platform is empowering SMEs, Tarebi Alebiosu, Founder, QShop, said the platform is a response to the challenges that SMEs face, especially accessing markets and payments processing. She said QShop, a technology-driven e-commerce platform founded in 2020, is on a mission to help Small and Medium Enterprises (SMEs) succeed in a technologically driven world. QShop’s integration with financial partners like Stripe, Flutterwave, Paystack and recently Providus Bank gives merchants the freedom to receive funds seamlessly and in any currency she noted adding that QShop’s recent partnership with Providus Bank has reduced payment processing time, allowing businesses to receive store credit for transactions in as little as one hour. Tarebi Alebiosu, Founder, QShop, further said: “Simply put, we are helping small businesses to sell online and scale easily. QShop is deeply integrated with social media allowing for a seamless and easy setup; most stores are up and running in 2 minutes or less.” Also commenting, Harrison Hammond, Head of Technology, QShop, said: “At QShop, we want to help customers grow from zero to a hundred with technology.”